# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dangerous-goods
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Acetone is miscible with water and serves as an important organic solvent in industry, home, and laboratory.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] About 6.7 million tonnes were produced worldwide in 2010, mainly for use as a solvent and for production of methyl methacrylate and bisphenol A, which are precursors to widely used plastics.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] It is a common building block in organic chemistry.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] It serves as a solvent in household products such as nail polish remover and paint thinner.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] It has volatile organic compound (VOC)-exempt status in the United States.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Acetone is produced and disposed of in the human body through normal metabolic processes.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Small quantities of it are present naturally in blood and urine.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] People with diabetic ketoacidosis produce it in larger amounts.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Medical ketogenic diets that increase ketone bodies (acetone, β-hydroxybutyric acid and acetoacetic acid) in the blood are used to suppress epileptic attacks in children with treatment-resistant epilepsy.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] From the 17th century, and before modern developments in organic chemistry nomenclature, acetone was given many different names.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] They included "spirit of Saturn", which was given when it was thought to be a compound of lead and, later, "pyro-acetic spirit" and "pyro-acetic ester".
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Prior to the name "acetone" being coined by French chemists, it was named "mesit" (from the Greek μεσίτης, meaning mediator) by Carl Reichenbach, who also said that methyl alcohol consisted of mesit and ethyl alcohol.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Names derived from mesit include mesitylene and mesityl oxide which were first synthesised from acetone.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] In 1839, the name "acetone" began to be used, because it was obtained from acetic acid.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Unlike many compounds with the *acet-* prefix which have a 2-carbon chain, acetone has a 3-carbon chain.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] That has caused confusion because there can not be a ketone with 2 carbons.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] The prefix refers to acetone's relation to vinegar (*acetum* in Latin, also the source of the words "acid" and "acetic"), rather than its chemical structure.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Acetone was first produced by Andreas Libavius in 1606 by distillation of lead(II) acetate.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] In 1832, French chemist Jean-Baptiste Dumas and German chemist Justus von Liebig determined the empirical formula for acetone.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] In 1833, French chemists Antoine Bussy and Michel Chevreul decided to name acetone by adding the suffix *-one* to the stem of the corresponding acid (viz, acetic acid) just as a similarly prepared product of what was then confused with margaric acid was named margarone.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] By 1852, Alexander William Williamson, an English chemist, realized that acetone was methyl acetyl; the following year, the French chemist Charles Frédéric Gerhardt concurred.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] In 1865, a German chemist, August Kekulé published the modern structural formula for acetone.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Johann Josef Loschmidt had presented the structure of acetone in 1861, but his privately published booklet received little attention.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] During World War I, Chaim Weizmann developed the biochemical process for industrial production of acetone (Weizmann Process).
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Acetone is produced directly or indirectly from propene.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Approximately 83% of acetone is produced via the cumene process; as a result, acetone production is tied to phenol production.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Other processes involve the direct oxidation of propylene (Wacker-Hoechst process), or the hydration of propylene to give 2-propanol, which is oxidized (dehydrogenated) to acetone.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Previously, acetone was produced by the dry distillation of acetates, for example calcium acetate in ketonic decarboxylation.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] After that time during World War I, acetone was produced using acetone-butanol-ethanol fermentation with *Clostridium acetobutylicum* bacteria, which was developed by Chaim Weizmann (later the first president of Israel) in order to help the British war effort, in the preparation of Cordite.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] This acetone-butanol-ethanol fermentation was eventually abandoned when newer methods with better yields were found.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] In 2010, the worldwide production capacity for acetone was estimated at 6.7 million tonnes per year.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] With 1.56 million tonnes per year, the United States had the highest production capacity, followed by Taiwan and China.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] The largest producer of acetone is INEOS Phenol, owning 17% of the world's capacity, with also significant capacity (7–8%) by Mitsui, Sunoco and Shell in 2010.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] INEOS Phenol also owns the world's largest production site (420,000 tonnes/annum) in Beveren, Belgium.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] The spot price of acetone in summer 2011 was 1100–1250 USD/tonne in the United States.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Humans exhale several milligrams of acetone per day and it arises from the decarboxylation of acetoacetate.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Small amounts of acetone are produced in the body by the decarboxylation of ketone bodies.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Certain dietary patterns including prolonged fasting and high-fat low-carbohydrate dieting, can produce ketosis, in which acetone is formed in body tissue.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Certain health conditions, such as alcoholism and diabetes, can produce ketoacidosis, uncontrollable ketosis that leads to a sharp, and potentially fatal, increase in the acidity of the blood.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Since it is a byproduct of fermentation, acetone is a byproduct of the distillery industry.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] It is produced by terrestrial vegetation, undefined ocean processes, incomplete combustion of biomass, or oxidation of hydrocarbons in the atmosphere.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Like most ketones, acetone exhibits the keto–enol tautomerism in which the nominal keto structure (CH3)2C=O of acetone itself is in equilibrium with the enol isomer (CH3)C(OH)=(CH2) (**prop-1-en-2-ol**).
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] In acetone vapor at ambient temperature, only 2.4×10−7% of the molecules are in the enol form.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] In the presence of suitable catalysts, two acetone molecules also combine to form the compound diacetone alcohol (CH3)C=O(CH2)C(OH)(CH3)2, which on dehydration gives mesityl oxide (CH3)C=O(CH)=C(CH3)2.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] This product can further combine with another acetone molecule, with loss of another molecule of water, yielding phorone and other compounds.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Acetone is a weak Lewis base that forms adducts with soft acids like I2 and hard acids like phenol.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Acetone also forms complexes with divalent metals.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Under ultraviolet light, acetone fluoresces.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] The flame temperature of pure acetone is 1980 °C.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] At its melting point (−96 °C) is claimed to polymerize to give a white elastic solid, soluble in acetone, stable for several hours at room temperature.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] To do so, a vapor of acetone is co-condensed with magnesium as a catalyst onto a very cold surface.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] The outcome of irradiation of acetone is wavelength dependent.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] The latter process is relevant to the atmospheric chemistry of acetone.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Acetone can then be metabolized either by CYP2E1 via methylglyoxal to D-lactate and pyruvate, and ultimately glucose/energy, or by a different pathway via propylene glycol to pyruvate, lactate, acetate (usable for energy) and propionaldehyde.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] About a third of the world's acetone is used as a solvent, and a quarter is consumed as acetone cyanohydrin, a precursor to methyl methacrylate.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Acetone is used to synthesize methyl methacrylate.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] The third major use of acetone (about 20%) is synthesizing bisphenol A.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Bisphenol A is a component of many polymers such as polycarbonates, polyurethanes, and epoxy resins.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Many millions of kilograms of acetone are consumed in the production of the solvents methyl isobutyl alcohol and methyl isobutyl ketone.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] These products arise via an initial aldol condensation to give diacetone alcohol.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Condensation with acetylene gives 2-methylbut-3-yn-2-ol, precursor to synthetic terpenes and terpenoids.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Acetone is a good solvent for many plastics and some synthetic fibers.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] It is used for thinning polyester resin, cleaning tools used with it, and dissolving two-part epoxies and superglue before they harden.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] It is used as one of the volatile components of some paints and varnishes.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Although itself flammable, acetone is used extensively as a solvent for the safe transportation and storage of acetylene, which cannot be safely pressurized as a pure compound.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Vessels containing a porous material are first filled with acetone followed by acetylene, which dissolves into the acetone.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] One litre of acetone can dissolve around 250 litres of acetylene at a pressure of 10 bars (1.0 MPa).
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Acetone is used as a solvent by the pharmaceutical industry and as a denaturant in denatured alcohol.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Acetone is also present as an excipient in some pharmaceutical drugs.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] A variety of organic reactions employ acetone as a polar, aprotic solvent, e.g. the Jones oxidation.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Because acetone is cheap, volatile, and dissolves or decomposes with most laboratory chemicals, an acetone rinse is the standard technique to remove solid residues from laboratory glassware before a final wash.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Despite common desiccatory use, acetone dries only via bulk displacement and dilution.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] It forms no azeotropes with water (see azeotrope tables).
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Acetone also removes certain stains from microscope slides.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] An acetone/dry ice mixture cools many low-temperature reactions.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Make-up artists use acetone to remove skin adhesive from the netting of wigs and mustaches by immersing the item in an acetone bath, then removing the softened glue residue with a stiff brush.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Acetone is a main ingredient in many nail polish removers because it breaks down nail polish.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] It is used for all types of nail polish removal, like gel nail polish, dip powder and acrylic nails.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] The chemical modifies peptides, both at α- or ε-amino groups, and in a poorly understood but rapid modification of certain glycine residues.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] In pathology, acetone helps find lymph nodes in fatty tissues (such as the mesentery) for tumor staging.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] The liquid dissolves the fat and hardens the nodes, making them easier to find.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Dermatologists use acetone with alcohol for acne treatments to chemically peel dry skin.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Common agents used for chemical peeling are salicylic acid, glycolic acid, azelaic acid, 30% salicylic acid in ethanol, and trichloroacetic acid (TCA).
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Prior to chemexfoliation, the skin is cleaned and excess fat removed in a process called defatting, using acetone, hexachlorophene, or a combination of these agents.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Acetone has been shown to have anticonvulsant effects in animal models of epilepsy, in the absence of toxicity, when administered in millimolar concentrations.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] It has been hypothesized that the high-fat low-carbohydrate ketogenic diet used clinically to control drug-resistant epilepsy in children works by elevating acetone in the brain.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Because of their higher energy requirements, children have higher acetone production than most adults – and the younger the child, the higher the expected production.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] This indicates that children are not uniquely susceptible to acetone exposure.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] External exposures are small compared to the exposures associated with the ketogenic diet.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Acetone has a relatively long lifetime in the atmosphere of about 2 weeks.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Because of its long lifetime, it can be transported by atmospheric winds to the upper troposphere and lower stratosphere where it can influence hydrogen radical (HOx) production and ozone (O3) levels.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] These two peroxy radicals can then undergo a series of reactions to produce hydrogen oxide radicals (HOx) and can therefore have a significant impact on atmospheric chemistry including concentration of ozone (O3) in the upper troposphere.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Photolysis is just one possible processes that removes acetone from the atmosphere.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Acetone can also be removed by ocean processes and by deposition to dry land surfaces.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] The contributions of each sink to the removal of acetone from the atmosphere is still not fully understood.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Acetone's most hazardous property is its extreme flammability.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] In small amounts, acetone burns with a dull blue flame; in larger amounts, fuel evaporation causes incomplete combustion and a bright yellow flame.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] When above acetone's flash point of −20 °C (−4 °F), air mixtures of 2.5‑12.8% acetone (by volume) may explode or cause a flash fire.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Vapors can flow along surfaces to distant ignition sources and flash back.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Static discharge may ignite acetone vapors, though acetone has a very high ignition initiation energy and accidental ignition is rare.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Acetone's auto-ignition temperature is relatively high 465 °C (869 °F); moreover, auto-ignition temperature depends upon experimental conditions, such as exposure time, and has been quoted as high as 535 °C.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Even pouring or spraying acetone over red-glowing coal will not ignite it, due to the high vapour concentration and the cooling effect of evaporation.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Acetone should be stored away from strong oxidizers, such as concentrated nitric and sulfuric acid mixtures.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] It may explode when stored with chloroform in the presence of a base.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] When oxidized without combustion, for example with hydrogen peroxide, acetone may form acetone peroxide, a highly unstable primary explosive.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Acetone peroxide may be formed accidentally, e.g. when waste peroxide is poured into waste solvents.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Acetone occurs naturally as part of certain metabolic processes in the human body, and has been studied extensively and is believed to exhibit only slight toxicity in normal use.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] There is no strong evidence of chronic health effects if basic precautions are followed.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] It is generally recognized to have low acute and chronic toxicity if ingested and/or inhaled.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Acetone is not regarded as a carcinogen, a mutagen, or a concern for chronic neurotoxicity effects.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Acetone can be found as an ingredient in a variety of consumer products ranging from cosmetics to processed and unprocessed foods.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] The United States Food and Drug Administration rates acetone as a generally recognized as safe (GRAS) substance when present in food and drink at concentrations from 5 to 8 mg/L.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Acetone is an irritant, causing mild skin and moderate-to-severe eye irritation.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Like many other solvents, acetone may depress the central nervous system at high vapor concentrations.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] Acute toxicity for mice by ingestion (LD50) is 3 g/kg, and by inhalation (LC50) is 44 g/m3 over 4 hours.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] In 1995, the United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) removed acetone from the list of volatile organic compounds.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] In making its decision EPA conducted an extensive review of the available toxicity data on acetone, which was continued through the 2000s.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetone] It found that the evaluable "data are inadequate for an assessment of the human carcinogenic potential of acetone".
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] As an alkyne, acetylene is unsaturated because its two carbon atoms are bonded together in a triple bond.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] The carbon–carbon triple bond places all four atoms in the same straight line, with CCH bond angles of 180°.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] The triple bond in acetylene results in a high energy content that is released when acetylene is burned.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Acetylene was discovered in 1836 by Edmund Davy, who identified it as a "new carburet of hydrogen".
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] It was an accidental discovery while attempting to isolate potassium metal.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] By heating potassium carbonate with carbon at very high temperatures, he produced a residue of what is now known as potassium carbide, (K2C2), which reacted with water to release the new gas.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] It was rediscovered in 1860 by French chemist Marcellin Berthelot, who coined the name *acétylène*.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Berthelot's empirical formula for acetylene (C4H2), as well as the alternative name "*quadricarbure d'hydrogène*" (hydrogen quadricarbide), were incorrect because many chemists at that time used the wrong atomic mass for carbon (6 instead of 12).
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Berthelot was able to prepare this gas by passing vapours of organic compounds (methanol, ethanol, etc.) through a red hot tube and collecting the effluent.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] He also found that acetylene was formed by sparking electricity through mixed cyanogen and hydrogen gases.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Berthelot later obtained acetylene directly by passing hydrogen between the poles of a carbon arc.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] It is a recovered side product in production of ethylene by cracking of hydrocarbons.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Approximately 400,000 tonnes were produced by this method in 1983.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Its presence in ethylene is usually undesirable because of its explosive character and its ability to poison Ziegler–Natta catalysts.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] It is selectively hydrogenated into ethylene, usually using Pd–Ag catalysts.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] This last reaction is implemented in the process of anaerobic decomposition of methane by microwave plasma.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] The first sample of acetylene produced was by Edmund Davy in 1836, via hydrolysis (decomposition using water) of potassium carbide.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] This reaction was discovered by Friedrich Wöhler in 1862, but a suitable commercial scale production method which allowed acetylene to be put into wider scale use was not found until 1892 by the Canadian inventor Thomas Willson while searching for a viable commercial production method for aluminum.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] As late as the early 21st century, China, Japan, and Eastern Europe produced acetylene primarily by this method.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] The use of this technology has since declined worldwide with the notable exception of China, with its emphasis on coal-based chemical industry, as of 2013.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Otherwise oil has increasingly supplanted coal as the chief source of reduced carbon.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Calcium carbide production requires high temperatures, ~2000 °C, necessitating the use of an electric arc furnace.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] In the US, this process was an important part of the late-19th century revolution in chemistry enabled by the massive hydroelectric power project at Niagara Falls.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] In terms of valence bond theory, in each carbon atom the 2s orbital hybridizes with one 2p orbital thus forming an sp hybrid.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] The other two 2p orbitals remain unhybridized.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] The two ends of the two sp hybrid orbital overlap to form a strong σ valence bond between the carbons, while on each of the other two ends hydrogen atoms attach also by σ bonds.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] The two unchanged 2p orbitals form a pair of weaker π bonds.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Since acetylene is a linear symmetrical molecule, it possesses the D∞h point group.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] At atmospheric pressure, acetylene cannot exist as a liquid and does not have a melting point.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] The triple point on the phase diagram corresponds to the melting point (−80.8 °C) at the minimal pressure at which liquid acetylene can exist (1.27 atm).
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] At temperatures below the triple point, solid acetylene can change directly to the vapour (gas) by sublimation.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] The sublimation point at atmospheric pressure is −84.0 °C.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] At room temperature and atmospheric pressure, the solubility of acetylene in acetone is 27.9 g per kg.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] For the same amount of dimethylformamide (DMF), the solubility is 51 g.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] At 20.26 bar, the solubility increases to 689.0 and 628.0 g for acetone and DMF, respectively.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] These solvents are used in pressurized gas cylinders.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Approximately 20% of acetylene is supplied by the industrial gases industry for oxyacetylene gas welding and cutting due to the high temperature of the flame.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Combustion of acetylene with oxygen produces a flame of over 3,600 K (3,330 °C; 6,020 °F), releasing 11.8 kJ/g.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Oxygen with acetylene is the hottest burning common gas mixture.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Oxy-acetylene welding was a popular welding process in previous decades.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] The development and advantages of arc-based welding processes have made oxy-fuel welding nearly extinct for many applications.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Acetylene usage for welding has dropped significantly.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Bell Canada cable-repair technicians still use portable acetylene-fuelled torch kits as a soldering tool for sealing lead sleeve splices in manholes and in some aerial locations.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Oxyacetylene welding may also be used in areas where electricity is not readily accessible.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Oxyacetylene cutting is used in many metal fabrication shops.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] For use in welding and cutting, the working pressures must be controlled by a regulator, since above 15 psi (100 kPa), if subjected to a shockwave (caused, for example, by a flashback), acetylene decomposes explosively into hydrogen and carbon.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Acetylene is useful for many processes, but few are conducted on a commercial scale.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] One of the major chemical applications is ethynylation of formaldehyde.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] The reaction gives butynediol, with propargyl alcohol as the by-product.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Copper acetylide is used as the catalyst.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] In addition to ethynylation, acetylene reacts with carbon monoxide to give acrylic acid, or acrylic esters.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] These derivatives form products such as acrylic fibers, glasses, paints, resins, and polymers.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Except in China, use of acetylene as a chemical feedstock has declined by 70% from 1965 to 2007 owing to cost and environmental considerations.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] In China, acetylene is a major precursor to vinyl chloride.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Prior to the widespread use of petrochemicals, coal-derived acetylene was a building block for several industrial chemicals.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Thus acetylene can be hydrated to give acetaldehyde, which in turn can be oxidized to acetic acid.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Processes leading to acrylates were also commercialized.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Almost all of these processes became obsolete with the availability of petroleum-derived ethylene and propylene.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] In 1881, the Russian chemist Mikhail Kucherov described the hydration of acetylene to acetaldehyde using catalysts such as mercury(II) bromide.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Before the advent of the Wacker process, this reaction was conducted on an industrial scale.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] The polymerization of acetylene with Ziegler–Natta catalysts produces polyacetylene films.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Polyacetylene, a chain of CH centres with alternating single and double bonds, was one of the first discovered organic semiconductors.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Its reaction with iodine produces a highly electrically conducting material.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Although such materials are not useful, these discoveries led to the developments of organic semiconductors, as recognized by the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 2000 to Alan J.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Heeger, Alan G MacDiarmid, and Hideki Shirakawa.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] In the 1920s, pure acetylene was experimentally used as an inhalation anesthetic.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Acetylene is sometimes used for carburization (that is, hardening) of steel when the object is too large to fit into a furnace.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Acetylene is used to volatilize carbon in radiocarbon dating.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] The carbonaceous material in an archeological sample is treated with lithium metal in a small specialized research furnace to form lithium carbide (also known as lithium acetylide).
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] The carbide can then be reacted with water, as usual, to form acetylene gas to feed into a mass spectrometer to measure the isotopic ratio of carbon-14 to carbon-12.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Acetylene combustion produces a strong, bright light and the ubiquity of carbide lamps drove much acetylene commercialization in the early 20th century.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Common applications included coastal lighthouses, street lights, and automobile and mining headlamps.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] In most of these applications, direct combustion is a fire hazard, and so acetylene has been replaced, first by incandescent lighting and many years later by low-power/high-lumen LEDs.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Nevertheless, acetylene lamps remain in limited use in remote or otherwise inaccessible areas and in countries with a weak or unreliable central electric grid.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] The energy richness of the C≡C triple bond and the rather high solubility of acetylene in water make it a suitable substrate for bacteria, provided an adequate source is available.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] A number of bacteria living on acetylene have been identified.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Acetylene is a moderately common chemical in the universe, often associated with the atmospheres of gas giants.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] One curious discovery of acetylene is on Enceladus, a moon of Saturn.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Natural acetylene is believed to form from catalytic decomposition of long-chain hydrocarbons at temperatures of 1,700 K (1,430 °C; 2,600 °F) and above.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Since such temperatures are highly unlikely on such a small distant body, this discovery is potentially suggestive of catalytic reactions within that moon, making it a promising site to search for prebiotic chemistry.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] In vinylation reactions, H−X compounds add across the triple bond.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Alcohols and phenols add to acetylene to give vinyl ethers.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Similarly, vinylpyrrolidone and vinylcarbazole are produced industrially by vinylation of 2-pyrrolidone and carbazole.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] The hydration of acetylene is a vinylation reaction, but the resulting vinyl alcohol isomerizes to acetaldehyde.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] The reaction is catalyzed by mercury salts.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] This reaction once was the dominant technology for acetaldehyde production, but it has been displaced by the Wacker process, which affords acetaldehyde by oxidation of ethylene, a cheaper feedstock.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] A similar situation applies to the conversion of acetylene to the valuable vinyl chloride by hydrochlorination versus the oxychlorination of ethylene.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Vinyl acetate is used instead of acetylene for some vinylations, which are more accurately described as transvinylations.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Higher esters of vinyl acetate have been used in the synthesis of vinyl formate.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Acetylene and its derivatives (2-butyne, diphenylacetylene, etc.) form complexes with transition metals.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Its bonding to the metal is somewhat similar to that of ethylene complexes.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Metal acetylides, species of the formula L*n*M−C2R, are also common.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Copper(I) acetylide and silver acetylide can be formed in aqueous solutions with ease due to a favorable solubility equilibrium.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Various organometallic and inorganic reagents are effective.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Acetylene can be semihydrogenated to ethylene, providing a feedstock for a variety of polyethylene plastics.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Acetylene is not especially toxic, but when generated from calcium carbide, or CaC2, it can contain toxic impurities such as traces of phosphine and arsine, which gives it a distinct garlic-like smell.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] It is also highly flammable, as are most light hydrocarbons, hence its use in welding.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Although it is stable at normal pressures and temperatures, if it is subjected to pressures as low as 15 psig it can explode.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] The safe limit for acetylene therefore is 101 kPagage, or 15 psig.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Additionally, if acetylene is initiated by intense heat or a shockwave, it can decompose explosively if the absolute pressure of the gas exceeds about 200 kilopascals (29 psi).
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] It is therefore supplied and stored dissolved in acetone or dimethylformamide (DMF), contained in a gas cylinder with a porous filling, which renders it safe to transport and use, given proper handling.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Acetylene cylinders should be used in the upright position to avoid withdrawing acetone during use.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Information on safe storage of acetylene in upright cylinders is provided by the OSHA, Compressed Gas Association, United States Mine Safety and Health Administration (MSHA), EIGA, and other agencies.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Copper catalyses the decomposition of acetylene, and as a result acetylene should not be transported in copper pipes.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Cylinders should be stored in an area segregated from oxidizers to avoid exacerbated reaction in case of fire/leakage.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Acetylene cylinders should not be stored in confined spaces, enclosed vehicles, garages, and buildings, to avoid unintended leakage leading to explosive atmosphere.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] In the US, National Electric Code (NEC) requires consideration for hazardous areas including those where acetylene may be released during accidents or leaks.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Consideration may include electrical classification and use of listed Group A electrical components in US.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] Further information on determining the areas requiring special consideration is in NFPA 497.
[src:dangerous-goods/acetylene] In Europe, ATEX also requires consideration for hazardous areas where flammable gases may be released during accidents or leaks.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] Manual fire suppression includes the use of a fire blanket, fire extinguisher, or a standpipe system.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] A fire blanket is a sheet of fire retardant material that is designed to be placed over a fire to smother it out.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] Small fire blankets are meant for inception stage fires.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] They are normally made of fiberglass or Kevlar.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] Larger ones can be found in laboratories and factories, and are designed to be wrapped around a person whose clothes have caught fire.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers are devices that contain and discharge a substance that extinguishes or puts out a fire.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] These handheld devices come in a huge range of sizes, but the most common are portable fire extinguishers, typically weighing up to 15 kg in total.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] These can be easily handled and operated by one person and placement can either be wall-mounted, on a fire extinguisher trolley or housed inside a cabinet.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers are one of the most common manual fire suppression devices and are required in all commercial buildings and vehicles.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers can be used with little to no training and are meant for small incipient stage fires.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] The most common extinguisher is the ABC extinguisher and are found in most offices and homes.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] It can be used on normal fires, liquid fires, and electrical fires.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] There are also special extinguishers for kitchen fires and for use on burning metals, those being Class K and Class D respectively.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] Standpipes are installed in most large, multistory buildings.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] There are two types of standpipes: dry and wet.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] Most standpipes are dry systems and cannot be used by the public.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] Dry systems require a fire engine to pump water into the system.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] Most dry systems do not have pre-connected hoses and require firefighters to bring in the hose.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] In wet systems, there is always water in the pipes and they can be used by anyone.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] Wet systems will have hoses so building occupants can try and extinguish fires.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] Wet systems are becoming less common with the increase in number of sprinkler systems being installed.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] In some systems, firefighters have the option of pumping a Fire Department Connection (FDC) which will increase the water pressure at a standpipe in the event of a fire pump failure or loss of pressure.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] Typically, these systems pressurize the sprinkler system or the standpipe but not both at the same time.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] Automatic control means are any form of suppression that requires no human intervention these can include a fire sprinkler system, a gaseous clean agent, or automatic foam suppression system.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] Most automatic suppression systems would be found in large commercial kitchens or other high-risk areas.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] Fire sprinkler systems are installed in all types of buildings, commercial and residential.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] They are usually located at ceiling level and are connected to a reliable water source, most commonly municipal water supply.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] A typical automatic sprinkler system operates when heat at the site of a fire causes a fusible link or glass component in the sprinkler head to fail, thereby releasing the water from the sprinkler head.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] This means that only the sprinkler heads at the fire location actuate – not all the sprinklers on a floor or in a building.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] However, certain systems, such as deluge systems, do spray water from all heads in the same zone upon actuation.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] Sprinkler systems help to reduce the growth of a fire, thereby increasing life safety and limiting structural damage.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] Gaseous clean agents are installed to result in less fire and water damage than sprinklers, such as in computer rooms.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] The system works by flooding an area with a gas which interferes with the fire tetrahedron.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] These systems are often found in areas where people are not going to be present when the system is activated such as datacenters, cooling systems, and other industrial applications.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] Activating a gaseous clean agent system when people are present can cause injury or death, and are usually equipped with an audible notification system to warn any potential occupants to evacuate the area.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] Automatic foam suppression systems come in three main forms low expansion, medium expansion, and high expansion.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] Low expansion foam expands less than 20 times its original size.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] These systems can be installed in a variety of places but are commonly found in places where hydrocarbons are stored.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] Low expansion foam systems when using film forming work by making a blanket of foam over the burning liquid to both cool it down and suppress the vapors.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] Medium expansion foam expands between 20 and 200 times its original size.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] These can be installed in outdoor settings like transfer stations or for use in open pits.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] Medium foam is used outdoors because it is denser than high expansion and will not blow away as easily.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] It works by covering what is on fire in a thick blanket of foam to smother it and suppress vapors.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] High expansion foam expands between 200 and 1000 times its original size.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] These systems are commonly installed in large volume areas like airplane hangars, mine shafts, and ship holds.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] These systems are normally installed inside and make a very light foam.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] They extinguish the fire by rapid smothering and cooling.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] Its rapid rate of expansion enables it to fill large areas with foam rapidly.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] When used on LNG tanks they provide an added insulation layer that helps reduce the vapor rate.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] Nozzles that are powered by electrical energy that is generated and supplied by fire detection and control devices and are typically closed.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] ILDFA uses a dual approach, combining a water-based fire suppression system in conjunction with a hollow, perforated flooring system to drain and remove spilled flammable liquid.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] This approach reduces the risk of pool fires inside infrastructure by diverting any leaked fuel away from potential ignition sources or by extinguishing any flammable liquid fire by depriving it of oxygen once it is removed.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] Fire detection works using smoke or heat sensors.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] These systems are very effective tool at alerting people in the immediate vicinity of where the fire is detected but building regulations require an integrated fire detection system.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] These system not only alerts people throughout the building by triggering the fire alarm but it can also summon emergency services.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] There are two types of systems available – addressable and conventional.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] Addressable systems monitor the specific location of each device (e.g. smoke detector, call point or sounder).
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] It means in the event of a fire or other emergency you know exactly where the problem is.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] This saves precious time and helps the emergency services prevent the loss of life and serious damage.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] Conventional systems can only determine the problem is in a general area and thus are more suited for small sites.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] When the fire detection system is activated it can also send an alert to the local fire department, broadcast a prerecorded warning message and unlock the buildings access control system.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] Hypoxic air fire prevention systems, also known as oxygen reduction systems are new automatic fire prevention systems that permanently reduce the oxygen concentration inside the protected volumes so that ignition or fire spreading cannot occur.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] Unlike traditional fire suppression systems that usually extinguish fire after it is detected, hypoxic air is able to prevent fires.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] At lower altitudes hypoxic air is safe to breathe for healthy individuals.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] All AFP systems are required to be installed and maintained in accordance with strict guidelines in order to maintain compliance with the local building code and the fire code.
[src:dangerous-goods/active-fire-protection] AFP works alongside modern architectural designs and construction materials and fire safety education to prevent, retard, and suppress structural fires.
[src:dangerous-goods/adr-treaty] Concluded in Geneva on 30 September 1957 under the aegis of the United Nations Economic Commission for Europe, it entered into force on 29 January 1968.
[src:dangerous-goods/adr-treaty] The agreement was modified (article 14, paragraph 3) in New York City on 21 August 1975, though these changes only took effect on 19 April 1985.
[src:dangerous-goods/adr-treaty] A new amended ADR 2011 entered into force on 1 January 2011.
[src:dangerous-goods/adr-treaty] Annexes A and B have been regularly amended and updated since the entry into force of ADR.
[src:dangerous-goods/adr-treaty] Consequently, to the amendments for entry into force on 1 January 2015 (until June 2017), a revised consolidated version has been published as document ECE/TRANS/242, Vol.
[src:dangerous-goods/adr-treaty] Every two years the regulations are updated with the latest version applicable being the ADR 2023.
[src:dangerous-goods/adr-treaty] The agreement itself is brief and simple, and its most important article is article 2.
[src:dangerous-goods/adr-treaty] Annex B regulates the construction, equipment, and use of vehicles for the transport of hazardous materials.
[src:dangerous-goods/adr-treaty] Consignment procedures, labeling, and marking of containers and vehicles.
[src:dangerous-goods/adr-treaty] Each entry in the different classes has been assigned a 4 digit UN number.
[src:dangerous-goods/adr-treaty] It is not usually possible to deduce the hazard class of a substance from its UN number: they have to be looked up in a table.
[src:dangerous-goods/adr-treaty] An exception to this are Class 1 substances whose UN number will always begin with a 0.
[src:dangerous-goods/adr-treaty] The ADR Secretariat has defined a classification system for major tunnels in Europe.
[src:dangerous-goods/adr-treaty] "The categorization [is] based on the assumption that in tunnels there are three major dangers [that] may cause numerous victims or serious damage to the tunnel structure." It is the responsibility of each national authority to categorize its tunnels accordingly.
[src:dangerous-goods/adr-treaty] The classes ranges from A (least restrictive), to E (most restrictive).
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] The idea of fighting forest fires from the air dates back at least as far as Friedrich Karl von Koenig-Warthausen's observations on seeing a blaze when overflying the Santa Lucia Range, California, in 1929.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] A wide variety of terminology has been used in the popular media for the aircraft (and methods) used in aerial firefighting.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] The terms **airtanker** or **air tanker** generally refer to fixed-wing aircraft based in the United States; "airtanker" is used in official documentation.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] The term "**waterbomber**" is used in some Canadian government documents for the same class of vehicles, though it sometimes has a connotation of amphibians.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] A wide variety of helicopters and fixed-wing aircraft are used for aerial firefighting.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] Forest Service and Bureau of Land Management own, lease, or contract for nearly 1,000 aircraft each fire season, with annual expenditures in excess of US$250 million in recent years".
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] Helicopters may be fitted with tanks (helitankers) or they may carry buckets.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] Some helitankers, such as the Erickson AirCrane, are also outfitted with a front-mounted foam cannon.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] Buckets are usually filled by submerging or dipping them in lakes, rivers, reservoirs, or portable tanks.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] The most popular of the buckets is the flexible Bambi Bucket.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] Tanks can be filled on the ground (by water tenders or truck-mounted systems) or water can be siphoned from lakes, rivers, reservoirs, or a portable tank through a hanging snorkel.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] Currently the world's largest helicopter, the Mil Mi-26, uses a Bambi bucket.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] The Mendocino Air Tanker Squad formed by Joseph Bolles Ely in 1956 was the first such unit in the United States to drop water and retardant on fires.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] Based at the Willows-Glenn County Airport it soon led the way for other agencies to form similar squads.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] Though World War II- and Korean War-era bombers were for a long time the mainstay of the aerial firefighting fleet, newer purpose-built tankers have since come online.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] The smallest are the Single Engine Air Tankers (SEATs).
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] These are agricultural sprayers that generally drop about 800 US gallons (3,000 L) of water or retardant.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] Examples include the Air Tractor AT-802, which can deliver around 800 gallons of water or fire retardant solution in each drop, and the Soviet Antonov An-2 biplane.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] Both of these aircraft can be fitted with floats that scoop water from the surface of a body of water.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] Similar in configuration to the World War II–era Consolidated PBY Catalina, the Canadair CL-215 and its derivative the CL-415 are designed and built specifically for firefighting.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] The Croatian Air Force uses six CL-415s as well as six AT 802s for firefighting purposes.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] Conair also converted a number of Convair 580 and Fokker F27 Friendship turboprop airliners to air tankers.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] The largest aerial firefighter ever used is a Boeing 747 aerial firefighter, known as the Global Supertanker, that can carry 19,600 US gallons (74,200 L) fed by a pressurized drop system.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] The Supertanker was deployed operationally for the first time in 2009, fighting a fire in Spain.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] The tanker made its first American operation on August 31, 2009, at the Oak Glen Fire.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] It has since been replaced by a Boeing 747-400.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] Another wide body jetliner that is currently being used as an air tanker is the modified McDonnell Douglas DC-10-30 operated by the 10 Tanker Air Carrier company as the DC-10 Air Tanker.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] It can carry up to 12,000 US gallons (45,400 L) of fire fighting retardant.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] The Russian Ministry of Emergency Situations operates convertible-to-cargo Ilyushin Il-76 airtankers that have been operating with 11,000-US-gallon (41,600 L) tanking systems, and several Beriev Be-200 jet powered amphibian aircraft.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] The Be-200 can carry a maximum payload of about 12,000 litres (3,200 US gal) of water, making "scoops" in suitable stretches of water in 14 seconds.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] Bombardier's Dash 8 Q Series aircraft are the basis of new, next-generation air tankers.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] Cascade Aerospace has converted two pre-owned Q400s to act as part-time water bomber and part-time transport aircraft for France's Sécurité Civile, while Neptune Aviation is converting a pre-owned Q300 as a prototype to augment its Lockheed P-2 Neptune aircraft.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] The Sécurité Civile also operates twelve Canadair CL-415 and nine Conair Turbo Firecat aircraft.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] Neptune Aviation also currently operates converted British Aerospace 146 jetliners as air tankers.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] The BAe 146 can carry up to 3,000 gallons of fire fighting retardant.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] Air Spray USA Ltd. of Chico, California has also converted the BAe 146 jetliner to the role of air tanker.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] Another modern-era passenger aircraft that has now been converted for aerial firefighting missions in the U.S. is the McDonnell Douglas MD-87 jetliner operated by Erickson Aero Tanker.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] The MD-87 can carry up to 4,000 gallons of fire fighting retardant.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] Coulson Aviation unveiled a Boeing 737-300 firefighting conversion in May 2017.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] Six aircraft have been purchased from Southwest Airlines for the RADS system conversion which was planned to enter service in December 2017.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] The 737 aircraft is smaller than the C-130Q which allows for a wider range of airfields to be utilized.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] Britt Coulson further stated the aircraft will be able to retain the current seat and galley configuration for tanker operations.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] On 22 November 2018, the 737 was used for the first time to fight a fire near Newcastle, Australia.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] In July 2022, Airbus tested the aerial firefighting capacity of the A400M using a roll-on/roll-off kit comprising a 20-tonne water tank and piping allowing the load to be expelled from the end of the cargo ramp.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] All links, citations and data sources are listed in the paragraph above.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] For accident and grounding citations, see paragraph below table.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] Other former military aircraft utilized as firefighting air tankers in the U.S. in the past included the B-17 and the PB4Y-2, a version of the B-24.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] The Lead Plane function directs the activities of the airtankers by both verbal target descriptions and by physically leading the airtankers on the drop run.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] The leadplane is typically referred to as a "Bird Dog" in Canada or "Supervision" aircraft in Australia.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] The O-2 Skymaster, Cessna 310 and OV-10 Bronco have been used as spotter and lead plane platforms.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] The Ontario Ministry of Natural Resources has also used the Cessna 337.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] The Beechcraft Baron was long used as a leadplane or air attack ship, but most were retired in 2003; more common now is the Beechcraft King Air and the Twin Commander 690.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] A Cessna Citation 500 jet owned by Air Spray (1967) LTd. was used by the British Columbia Ministry of Forests beginning in 1995 and used for two fire seasons to lead the very fast Electra L188 air tanker to the fires.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] This was the first time a jet aircraft was used as a lead plane or "bird dog".
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] The Department of Parks and Wildlife in Western Australia operates a fleet of nine American Champion Scouts 8GCBC during the summer months as spotter aircraft and Air Attack platforms.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] The Provinces of Alberta and British Columbia and the Yukon Territories contract to supply Twin Commander 690 as bird dog aircraft for their air tanker fleets.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] Air Spray owns 9 Twin Commander 690 for use as bird dog aircraft.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] In the United States, most of these aircraft are privately owned and contracted to government agencies, and the National Guard and the U.S.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] Marines also maintain fleets of firefighting aircraft.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] Forest Service (USFS) and the Bureau of Land Management (BLM) announced that they were cancelling contracts with operators of 33 heavy airtankers.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] They cited liability concerns and an inability to safely manage the fleet after the wing failure and resulting crash of a C-130A Hercules in California and a PB4Y-2 in Colorado during the summer of 2002.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] Both aged aircraft broke up in flight due to catastrophic fatigue cracks at the wing roots.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] After subsequent third-party examination and extensive testing of all USFS contracted heavy airtankers, three companies were awarded contracts and now maintain a combined fleet of 23 aircraft.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] Borate salts used in the past to fight wildfires have been found to sterilize the soil and be toxic to animals so are now prohibited.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] Newer retardants use ammonium sulfate or ammonium polyphosphate with attapulgite clay thickener or diammonium phosphate with a guar gum derivative thickener.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] Fire retardants often contain wetting agents, preservatives and rust inhibitors and are colored red with ferric oxide or fugitive color to mark where they have been dropped.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] Brand names of fire retardants for aerial application include Fortress and Phos-Chek.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] Some water-dropping aircraft carry tanks of a guar gum derivative to thicken the water and reduce runoff.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] Helicopters can hover over the fire and drop water or retardant.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] The S-64 Helitanker has microprocessor-controlled doors on its tank.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] The doors are controlled based on the area to be covered and wind conditions.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] Fixed-wing aircraft must make a pass and drop water or retardant like a bomber.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] Water is not usually dropped directly on flames because its effect is short-lived.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] Fire retardants are not typically used to extinguish the fire, but instead are used to contain the fire, or slow it down to allow ground crews to contain it.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] Because of this, retardants are usually dropped in front of or around a moving fire, rather than directly on it, creating a firebreak.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] Aerial firefighting is most effectively used in conjunction with ground-based efforts, as aircraft are only one weapon in the firefighting arsenal.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] However, there have been cases of aircraft extinguishing fires long before ground crews were able to reach them.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] Some firefighting aircraft can refill their tanks in mid-flight, by flying down to skim the surface of large bodies of water.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] This is particularly useful in rural areas where flying back to an airbase for refills may take too much time.
[src:dangerous-goods/aerial-firefighting] In 2002 an Ontario CL-415 crew was able to refill 100 times within a 4-hour mission, delivering 162,000 US gallons (613,240 L) or 1,350,000 pounds (612 t) of water on a fire near Dryden, Ontario (June 1, 2002 Dryden fire # 10 Tanker #271 civil ident C-GOGE).
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] The use of ANFO originated in the 1950s.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] It is highly insensitive as an explosive, requiring a quantity of secondary explosive, known as a primer or a booster (larger than a standard blasting cap), in order to be detonated.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] It has found wide use in coal mining, quarrying, metal ore mining, and civil construction in applications where its low cost and ease of use may outweigh the benefits of other explosives, such as water resistance, oxygen balance, higher detonation velocity, or performance in small-diameter columns.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] The mining industry accounts for an estimated 90% of the more than 5.5 million pounds (2.5 thousand tonnes) of explosives used annually in the United States.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] ANFO is also widely used in avalanche hazard mitigation.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] ANFO mixed with nitromethane as the fuel is known as ANNM.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] The chemistry of ANFO detonation is the reaction of ammonium nitrate with a long-chain alkane hydrocarbon (CnH2n+2) to form nitrogen, carbon dioxide, and steam.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] In an ideal stoichiometrically balanced reaction, ANFO is composed of about 94.5% AN and 5.5% FO by weight.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] In practice, a slight excess of fuel oil is added, as underdosing results in reduced performance while overdosing merely results in more post-blast fumes.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] When detonation conditions are optimal, the gases are the only products.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] In practical use, such conditions are impossible to attain, and blasts produce moderate amounts of toxic gases such as carbon monoxide and nitrogen oxides (NOx).
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] The fuel component of ANFO is typically diesel fuel, but kerosene, coal dust, racing fuels like nitromethane, or even molasses have been used instead.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] Finely powdered aluminium in the mixture will sensitise it to detonate more readily.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] ANFO is highly insensitive, making it a tertiary explosive (or a "blasting agent").
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] Without a sensitizer, it cannot be detonated by a typical blasting cap (such as a No.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] A larger quantity of secondary explosive, known as a primer or a booster, must be used.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] One or two sticks of dynamite were historically used; current practice is to use Tovex or cast boosters of pentolite (TNT/PETN or similar compositions).
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] ANFO is technically a high explosive in that it decomposes through detonation rather than deflagration at a velocity higher than the speed of sound in the material, but the low sensitivity means that it is not generally regulated as such.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] ANFO has a moderate velocity compared to other industrial explosives, measuring 3,200 m/s in 130 mm (5 in) diameter, unconfined, at ambient temperature.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] It is described as a *non-ideal high explosive*, as its explosive velocity is far from the thermodynamic ideal due to its porosity and the phase separation of its two components.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] In the mining industry, the term ANFO specifically describes a mixture of solid ammonium nitrate prills and diesel fuel.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] Other explosives based on the ANFO chemistry exist; the most commonly used are emulsions.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] They differ from ANFO in the physical form the reactants take.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] The most notable properties of emulsions are water resistance and higher bulk density.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] While the density of pure crystalline ammonium nitrate is 1700 kg/m3, individual prills of explosive-grade AN measure approximately 1300 kg/m3.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] Their lower density is due to the presence of a small spherical air pocket within each prill: this is the primary difference between AN sold for blasting and that sold for agricultural use.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] These voids are necessary to sensitize ANFO: they create so-called "hot spots".
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] Finely powdered aluminium can be added to ANFO to increase both sensitivity and energy; in commercial usages however, this has fallen out of favor due to cost.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] ANFO has a bulk density of about 840 kg/m3.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] In surface mining applications, it is typically loaded into boreholes by dedicated trucks that mix the AN and FO components immediately before the product is dispensed.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] In underground mining applications, ANFO is typically blow-loaded.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] AN is highly hygroscopic, readily absorbing water from air.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] In humid environments, absorbed water interferes with its explosive function.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] AN is fully water-soluble; as such, it cannot be loaded into boreholes that contain standing water.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] When used in wet mining conditions, considerable effort must be taken to remove standing water and install a liner in the borehole; it is generally more productive to instead use a water-resistant explosive such as emulsion.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] Ammonium nitrate is widely used as a fertilizer in the agricultural industry.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] In many countries, its purchase and use are restricted to buyers who have obtained the proper license.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] In most jurisdictions, ammonium nitrate does not need to be classified as an explosive for transport purposes; it is merely an oxidizer.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] Mines typically prepare ANFO on-site using the same diesel fuel that powers their vehicles.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] While many fuels can theoretically be used, the low volatility and cost of diesel make it ideal.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] ANFO under most conditions is detonator-insensitive, so it is legally classified as a blasting agent (tertiary explosive) and not a high explosive.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] Environmental hazards include eutrophication in confined waters and nitrate/gas oil contamination of ground or surface water.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] ANFO was used in 1970 when protests by students became violent at the University of Wisconsin–Madison, who learned how to make and use ANFO from a Wisconsin Conservation Department booklet entitled *Pothole Blasting for Wildlife*, resulting in the Sterling Hall bombing.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] ANFO used to be widely used by the FLNC (National Liberation Front of Corsica), along with f15 explosive.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] Five containers of 500 kilograms (1,100 pounds) each were used to blow up the Tax Office building in Bastia on 28 February 1987.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] The ANFO car bomb was adopted by the Provisional IRA in 1972 and, by 1973, the Troubles were consuming 21,000 kilograms (47,000 pounds) of ammonium nitrate for the majority of bombs.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] The Ulster Volunteer Force (UVF) also made use of ANFO bombs, often mixing in gelignite as a booster, in the Dublin and Monaghan bombings of May 1974 which killed 34 people & injured almost 300, ANFO car bombs were used in Dublin.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] It has also seen use by groups such as the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia and ETA.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] In 1992, Shining Path perpetrated the Tarata bombing in Lima, Peru, using two ANFO truck bombs.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] A similar setup, mixed with nitromethane, was used in the 1995 Oklahoma City bombing by American anti-government extremist Timothy McVeigh and his accomplices to target the Alfred P.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] Murrah Federal Building in Oklahoma City, killing 168 and inuring 684.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] The Shijiazhuang bombings rocked the city of Shijiazhuang, China, on 16 March 2001.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] A total of 108 people were killed, and 38 others injured when, within a short time, several ANFO bombs exploded near four apartment buildings.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] In April 2010, police in Greece confiscated 180 kg of ANFO and other related material stashed in a hideaway in the Athens suburb of Kareas.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] The material was believed to be linked to attacks previously carried out by the "Revolutionary Struggle" terrorist group.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] In January 2010, President Hamid Karzai of Afghanistan also issued a decree banning the use, production, storage, purchase, or sale of ammonium nitrate, after an investigation showed militants in the Taliban insurgency had used the substance in bomb attacks.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] On 22 July 2011, an aluminum powder-enriched ANNM explosive, with total size of 950 kg (150 kg of aluminium powder), increasing demolition power by 10–30% over plain ANFO, was used in the Oslo bombing.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] On 13 April 2016, two suspected IRA members were stopped in Dublin with 67 kg of ANFO.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] On 6 March 2018, eight members of the extreme right neo-Nazi group Combat 18 were arrested in Athens, Greece, accused of multiple attacks on immigrants and activists.
[src:dangerous-goods/anfo] They had 50 kg of ANFO in their possession.
[src:dangerous-goods/astm-international] In 1898, a group of scientists and engineers, led by chemist, industry leader, and proponent of standardization Charles Dudley, formed the American Society for Testing Material (ASTM) to address the frequent rail breaks affecting the fast-growing railroad industry.
[src:dangerous-goods/astm-international] The group developed a standard for the steel used to fabricate rails.
[src:dangerous-goods/astm-international] In 1961 the name "American Society for Testing and Materials" was adopted.
[src:dangerous-goods/astm-international] In 2001, ASTM officially changed its name to "ASTM International" and added the tagline "Standards Worldwide".
[src:dangerous-goods/astm-international] In 2014, the tagline changed to "Helping our World Work better." ASTM International had offices in Belgium, Canada, China, Peru, Washington, D.C., and West Conshohocken, PA.
[src:dangerous-goods/astm-international] In April 2016, the Safety Equipment Institute (SEI) became a subsidiary of ASTM International.
[src:dangerous-goods/astm-international] SEI is an accredited third-party certification organization that certifies various types of personal protective equipment to industry consensus standards.
[src:dangerous-goods/astm-international] On June 9, 2022, it was announced that the European Committee for Standardization (CEN) and ASTM International agreed to extend and expand a Technical Cooperation Agreement from 2019.
[src:dangerous-goods/astm-international] Membership in the organization is open to anyone interested in its activities.
[src:dangerous-goods/astm-international] Standards are developed within committees, and new committees are formed as needed, upon request of interested members.
[src:dangerous-goods/astm-international] Membership in most committees is voluntary and is initiated by the member's request, not by appointment or invitation.
[src:dangerous-goods/astm-international] Members are classified as users, producers, consumers, and "general interest".
[src:dangerous-goods/astm-international] The latter includes academics and consultants.
[src:dangerous-goods/astm-international] Users include industry users, who may be producers in the context of other technical commodities, and end-users such as consumers.
[src:dangerous-goods/astm-international] To meet the requirements of antitrust laws, producers must constitute less than 50% of every committee or subcommittee, and votes are limited to one per producer company.
[src:dangerous-goods/astm-international] Because of these restrictions, there can be a substantial waiting-list of producers seeking organizational memberships on the more popular committees.
[src:dangerous-goods/astm-international] Members can participate without a formal vote and their input will be fully considered.
[src:dangerous-goods/astm-international] As of 2015, ASTM has more than 30,000 members, including over 1,150 organizational members, from more than 140 countries.
[src:dangerous-goods/astm-international] The members serve on one or more of 140+ ASTM Technical Committees.
[src:dangerous-goods/astm-international] ASTM International has several awards for contributions to standards authorship, including the ASTM International Award of Merit (the organization's highest award) ASTM International is classified by the United States Internal Revenue Service as a 501(c)(3) nonprofit organization.
[src:dangerous-goods/astm-international] In 2018, ASTM International launched the Additive Manufacturing Center of Excellence (AM CoE), a global initiative uniting industry, government, and academia to accelerate research, development, standardization, certification, and industrialization of additive manufacturing (AM).
[src:dangerous-goods/astm-international] Headquartered in Washington, D.C., with a network of experts across the Americas, Europe, and Asia, the AM CoE focuses on bridging the gap between cutting-edge research and consensus-based standards.
[src:dangerous-goods/astm-international] These initiatives aim to close standardization gaps, support qualification frameworks, and promote the broader adoption of additive manufacturing technologies across the aerospace, defense industry, medical devices, automotive industry, and energy sectors.
[src:dangerous-goods/astm-international] In 2021, ASTM International acquired Wohlers Associates, a consulting firm and market intelligence provider in additive manufacturing and 3D printing.
[src:dangerous-goods/astm-international] Wohlers Associates provides industry analysis and forecasts covering hardware, software, materials, and applications related to additive manufacturing.
[src:dangerous-goods/astm-international] Funded by the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST), the Standardization Center of Excellence (SCOE) is a more recent initiative under ASTM International.
[src:dangerous-goods/astm-international] SCOE focuses on advancing innovation and standardization for critical and emerging technologies, offering a coordinated framework connecting R&D, standards development, workforce readiness, and regulatory alignment.
[src:dangerous-goods/astm-international] The SCOE enables cross-industry collaboration to ensure that next-generation technologies are developed, validated, and deployed with trusted, globally harmonized standards.
[src:dangerous-goods/astm-international] ASTM International has no role in requiring or enforcing compliance with its standards.
[src:dangerous-goods/astm-international] The standards may become mandatory when referenced by an external contract, corporation, regulation, law, or government.
[src:dangerous-goods/astm-international] In the United States, ASTM standards have been adopted by incorporation or reference in many federal, state, and municipal government regulations.
[src:dangerous-goods/astm-international] The 1995 National Technology Transfer and Advancement Act requires the Federal government to use privately developed consensus standards whenever possible.
[src:dangerous-goods/astm-international] The Act reflects what had long been recommended as best practice within the Federal government.
[src:dangerous-goods/astm-international] Other governments, including state and foreign, have also referenced ASTM standards.
[src:dangerous-goods/astm-international] Corporations doing international business may choose to reference an ASTM standard.
[src:dangerous-goods/astm-international] All toys sold in the United States must meet the safety requirements of ASTM F963, Standard Consumer Safety Specification for Toy Safety, as part of the Consumer Product Safety Improvement Act (CPSIA) of 2008.
[src:dangerous-goods/astm-international] The law makes the ASTM F963 standard a mandatory requirement for toys while the Consumer Product Safety Commission (CPSC) studies the standard's effectiveness and issues final consumer guidelines for toy safety.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] Hazardous materials are often subject to chemical regulations.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] Hazmat teams are personnel specially trained to handle dangerous goods, which include materials that are radioactive, flammable, explosive, corrosive, oxidizing, asphyxiating, biohazardous, toxic, poisonous, pathogenic, or allergenic.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] Also included are physical conditions such as compressed gases and liquids or hot materials, including all goods containing such materials or chemicals, or may have other characteristics that render them hazardous in specific circumstances.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] Dangerous goods are often indicated by diamond-shaped signage on the item (see NFPA 704), its container, or the building where it is stored.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] The color of each diamond indicates its hazard, e.g., flammable is indicated with red, because fire and heat are generally of red color, and explosive is indicated with orange, because mixing red (flammable) with yellow (oxidizing agent) creates orange.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] A nonflammable and nontoxic gas is indicated with green, because all compressed air vessels were this color in France after World War II, and France was where the diamond system of hazmat identification originated.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] The most widely applied regulatory scheme is that for the transportation of dangerous goods.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] The United Nations Economic and Social Council issues the *UN Recommendations on the Transport of Dangerous Goods*, which form the basis for most regional, national, and international regulatory schemes.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] For instance, the International Civil Aviation Organization has developed dangerous goods regulations for air transport of hazardous materials that are based upon the UN model but modified to accommodate unique aspects of air transport.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] Individual airline and governmental requirements are incorporated with this by the International Air Transport Association to produce the widely used IATA *Dangerous Goods Regulations* (DGR).
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] Similarly, the International Maritime Organization (IMO) has developed the International Maritime Dangerous Goods Code ("IMDG Code", part of the International Convention for the Safety of Life at Sea) for transportation of dangerous goods by sea.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] IMO member countries have also developed the HNS Convention to provide compensation in case of dangerous goods spills in the sea.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] The Intergovernmental Organisation for International Carriage by Rail has developed the regulations concerning the International Carriage of Dangerous Goods by Rail ("RID", part of the Convention concerning International Carriage by Rail).
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] Many individual nations have also structured their dangerous goods transportation regulations to harmonize with the UN model in organization as well as in specific requirements.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] The Globally Harmonized System of Classification and Labelling of Chemicals (GHS) is an internationally agreed upon system set to replace the various classification and labeling standards used in different countries.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] The GHS uses consistent criteria for classification and labeling on a global level.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] Dangerous goods are assigned to UN numbers and proper shipping names according to their hazard classification and their composition.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] Dangerous goods commonly carried are listed in the Dangerous Goods list.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] Dangerous goods are divided into nine classes (in addition to several subcategories) on the basis of the specific chemical characteristics producing the risk.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] Note: The graphics and text in this article representing the dangerous goods safety marks are derived from the United Nations-based system of identifying dangerous goods.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] Not all countries use precisely the same graphics (label, placard or text information) in their national regulations.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] Some use graphic symbols, but without English wording or with similar wording in their national language.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] Refer to the dangerous goods transportation regulations of the country of interest.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] For example, see the *TDG Bulletin: Dangerous Goods Safety Marks* based on the Canadian Transportation of Dangerous Goods Regulations.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] The statement above applies equally to all the dangerous goods classes discussed in this article.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] Mitigating the risks associated with hazardous materials may require the application of safety precautions during their transport, use, storage and disposal.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] Most countries regulate hazardous materials by law, and they are subject to several international treaties as well.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] Even so, different countries may use different class diamonds for the same product.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] For example, in Australia, anhydrous ammonia UN 1005 is classified as 2.3 (toxic gas) with subsidiary hazard 8 (corrosive), whereas in the U.S. it is only classified as 2.2 (non-flammable gas).
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] People who handle dangerous goods will often wear protective equipment, and metropolitan fire departments often have a response team specifically trained to deal with accidents and spills.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] Persons who may come into contact with dangerous goods as part of their work are also often subject to monitoring or health surveillance to ensure that their exposure does not exceed occupational exposure limits.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] Laws and regulations on the use and handling of hazardous materials may differ depending on the activity and status of the material.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] For example, one set of requirements may apply to their use in the workplace while a different set of requirements may apply to spill response, sale for consumer use, or transportation.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] Most countries regulate some aspect of hazardous materials.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] Packing groups are used for the purpose of determining the degree of protective packaging required for dangerous goods during transportation.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] One of the transport regulations is that, as an assistance during emergency situations, written instructions how to deal in such need to be carried and easily accessible in the driver's cabin.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] Dangerous goods shipments also require a dangerous goods transport document prepared by the shipper.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] The information that is generally required includes the shipper's name and address; the consignee's name and address; descriptions of each of the dangerous goods, along with their quantity, classification, and packaging; and emergency contact information.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] Common formats include the one issued by the International Air Transport Association (IATA) for air shipments and the form by the International Maritime Organization (IMO) for sea cargo.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] A license or permit card for hazmat training must be presented when requested by officials.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] The international community has defined the responsible management of hazardous waste and chemicals as an important part of sustainable development with Sustainable Development Goal 3.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] The Australian Dangerous Goods Code complies with international standards of importation and exportation of dangerous goods in line with the UN Recommendations on the Transport of Dangerous Goods.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] Australia uses the standard international UN numbers with a few slightly different signs on the back, front and sides of vehicles carrying hazardous substances.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] The country uses the same "Hazchem" code system as the UK to provide advisory information to emergency services personnel in the event of an emergency.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] Transportation of dangerous goods (hazardous materials) in Canada by road is normally a provincial jurisdiction.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] The federal government has jurisdiction over air, most marine, and most rail transport.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] The federal government acting centrally created the federal *Transportation of Dangerous Goods Act* and regulations, which provinces adopted in whole or in part via provincial transportation of dangerous goods legislation.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] The result is that all provinces use the federal regulations as their standard within their province; some small variances can exist because of provincial legislation.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] Creation of the federal regulations was coordinated by Transport Canada.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] Hazard classifications are based upon the UN model.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] Outside of federal facilities, labour standards are generally under the jurisdiction of individual provinces and territories.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] However, communication about hazardous materials in the workplace has been standardized across the country through Health Canada's Workplace Hazardous Materials Information System (WHMIS).
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] The European Union has passed numerous directives and regulations to avoid the dissemination and restrict the usage of hazardous substances, important ones being the Restriction of Hazardous Substances Directive (RoHS) and the REACH regulation.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] There are also long-standing European treaties such as ADR, ADN and RID that regulate the transportation of hazardous materials by road, rail, river and inland waterways, following the guide of the UN model regulations.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] European Union law distinguishes clearly between the law of dangerous goods and the law of hazardous materials.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] The first refers primarily to the transport of the respective goods including the interim storage, if caused by the transport.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] The latter describes the requirements of storage (including warehousing) and usage of hazardous materials.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] This distinction is important because different directives and orders of European law are applied.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] The United Kingdom (as well as Australia, Malaysia, and New Zealand) uses the Hazchem warning plate system which carries information on how an emergency service should deal with an incident.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] The *Dangerous Goods Emergency Action Code List* (EAC) lists dangerous goods; it is reviewed every two years and is an essential compliance document for all emergency services, local government and for those who may control the planning for, and prevention of, emergencies involving dangerous goods.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] The latest 2025 version is available from the National Chemical Emergency Centre (NCEC) website.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] Guidance is available from the Health and Safety Executive.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] New Zealand's Land Transport Rule: Dangerous Goods 2005 and the Dangerous Goods Amendment 2010 describe the rules applied to the transportation of hazardous and dangerous goods in New Zealand.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] The system closely follows the United Nations Recommendations on the Transport of Dangerous Goods and uses placards with Hazchem codes and UN numbers on packaging and the transporting vehicle's exterior to convey information to emergency services personnel.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] Drivers that carry dangerous goods commercially, or carry quantities in excess of the rule's guidelines must obtain a D (dangerous goods) endorsement on their driver's licence.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] Drivers carrying quantities of goods under the rule's guidelines and for recreational or domestic purposes do not need any special endorsements.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] The Pipeline and Hazardous Materials Safety Administration regulates hazmat transportation within the territory of the US by *Title 49 of the Code of Federal Regulations*.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] In 1984 the agencies OSHA, EPA, USCG, and NIOSH jointly published the first *Hazardous Waste Operations and Emergency Response Guidance Manual* which is available for download.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] The Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) regulates hazardous materials as they may impact the community and environment, including specific regulations for environmental cleanup and for handling and disposal of waste hazardous materials.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] For instance, transportation of hazardous materials is regulated by the Hazardous Materials Transportation Act.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] The Resource Conservation and Recovery Act and analogous state laws were also passed to further protect human and environmental health.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] The Consumer Product Safety Commission regulates hazardous materials that may be used in products sold for household and other consumer uses.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] Following the UN model, the DOT divides regulated hazardous materials into nine classes, some of which are further subdivided.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] Hazardous materials in transportation must be placarded and have specified packaging and labelling.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] Some materials must always be placarded, others may only require placarding in certain circumstances.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] Trailers of goods in transport are usually marked with a four digit UN number.
[src:dangerous-goods/dangerous-goods] This number, along with standardized logs of hazmat information, can be referenced by first responders (firefighters, police officers, and ambulance personnel) who can find information about the material in the *Emergency Response Guidebook*.
